\hypertarget{latex}{%
\paragraph{Latex}\label{latex}}

Latex:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  describes content and layout for PDF files
\item
  long-standing standard for scientific publishing
\item
  aims to separate content from presentation
\item
  can handle complex formulas and layouts
\item
  gives stable output on different platforms
\item
  has a process to include bibliograpy
\item
  often a preferred format for journal submissions
\end{itemize}

Drawbacks:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  the price you pay is overhead: large installation pakages and document
  manipulations requires skill
\item
  not too readable without prior knowledge, very hard to write from
  scratch\\
\item
  easier when working on an existing project or working in a template
\end{itemize}

Cutting edge:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \href{https://blog.typeset.io/the-only-latex-editor-guide-youll-need-in-2018-e63868fae027}{online
  editors} cut down installation burden and provide visual functionality
\item
  \ldots{} yet you loose some of control over files
\item
  alternative is git-based workflow to handle
\end{itemize}

Stories:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \href{https://3d.bk.tudelft.nl/ken/en/2016/04/02/my-latex-thesis-workflow.html}{1}
\item
  \href{http://pierog.it/en/2018/03/markdown-workflow/}{2}
\end{itemize}

