\hypertarget{takeaways}{%
\section{Takeaways}\label{takeaways}}

\begin{verbatim}

domain,                                research finding             contribution
idea,
problem                                service/product              utility

                                                                    clarity

              theory

              data, evidence

              methods, code

              previous findings


                              images

                              tables

                              text

                                       book

                                       report
                    
                                       research article              readers

                                       commentary

                                       documentation                 users

                                       service, product
\end{verbatim}

Choice of reporting format depends on: - ratios of code/images to prose
- layout complexity - maths - end user expectations about delievery
(time to market, reproducible)

Names: - learning \texttt{markdown} is highly recommended -
\texttt{jupiter} notebooks are here to stay (enhance your experience
with \texttt{nbconvert}) - learn \texttt{pandoc} to see how you can
convert between different formats quickly - invest in \texttt{latex}, if
you will have to work with them in your domain field

